\[\sec^2 \theta = 1 + \tan^2 \theta = 1 + (-2\sqrt{2})^2 = 9,\]so $\sec \theta = -3$ (since $\theta$ is in the second quadrant).  Then $\cos \theta = -\frac{1}{3},$ so
\[\sin \theta = \sqrt{1 - \cos^2 \theta} = \sqrt{1 - \frac{1}{9}} = \boxed{\frac{4\sqrt{2}}{9}} = \frac{4}{\sqrt{18 + 8\sqrt{2}}}.\]
